# Code Style

## Core Principles

- **Never nest** — early returns, flat code. If you're indenting more than once, refactor
- **No narration comments** — code speaks for itself. Only comment non-obvious intent or trade-offs. Never `// Get the file`, `// Return result`, or section banners
- **No magic values in rule config** — use named constants in `rules.js` (e.g. `error`, `off`, `maxLinesPerFile`, `maxComplexity`)
- **Deduplicate ruthlessly** — shared logic in shared modules
- **Simple over clever** — readable beats terse
- **Descriptive names** — `maxLinesPerFile` not `max`
- **Verb-driven function names** — prefer `get`, `remove`, `create`, `list`, `put`, `update` over `fetch`, `delete`, `post`. Name functions for what they do, not the HTTP method
- **Types in dedicated files** — interfaces, enums, and types live in `types.ts`. Never scatter type definitions across implementation files
- **Defensive guards** — double-check assumptions with `if` checks and logging. Don't trust that data is what you expect — verify and log when it isn't
- **Generators when appropriate** — use generator functions for iteration, lazy evaluation, and streaming patterns where they simplify the code

## Naming Conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Files | kebab-case | `eslint.config.js`, `rules.js`, `utils.js` |
| Rule group vars | camelCase | `commonjsPreventRules`, `stylisticTs`, `tsEslint` |
| Constants | camelCase | `maxClasses`, `printWidth`, `newlineCount` |
| Severity/options | Use destructured consts | `error`, `off`, `always`, `never` |

## File Organization

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `rules.js` | Rule groups and merged `rules`; exports for config |
| `utils.js` | Helpers for config (getTsConfigFile, debug); Node only |
| `eslint.config.js` | Flat config entry; requires rules and utils |

## Imports (rules.js / eslint.config.js)

- External packages first (require)
- Internal: `./rules.js`, `./utils.js` (relative)

## Creo Standards

- **Releases**: `creo-team/action-release` via `github-release.yaml` workflow
- **Versions**: bare semver — never prefix with `v`
- **Commits**: conventional commits (`feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`), one change per commit
